{"/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_american_ver02/data/sn88085620/00211107601/1910090201/0381.xml":{"full_text":"HAVE YOU\nREGISTERED\nVOL. XX.\nCHARLES PERRY TAYLOR\nSecretary-Treasurer Washington Slate Federation of Labor.\nLessons That Labor Day Should Teach\nto the Men and Women of Toil\nBy Charles Perry Tuylor\nVgain we arc to celebrate the in\ndependence and dignity of Labor. One\nday in the year i-- our own. What shall\nwe do with it? To my mind, we can\nput it to no better use than by giving\nthought to our needs, hopes and aspira\ntions, to consider our duty industrially\nmid politically, and by demonstrating\nto all who would observe our firm faith\nin our labor organizations and deter\nmination to stand by them.\nWith all our boasted modern civiliza\ntion, labor conditions in the United\nStates nre at many points most intol\nerable. The premature employment of\nchildren is the evil that has attracted\n-est attention, but there are other\nevils equally serious. Thousands of\ntvonjen and girls, prospective mothers\nof the nation, work long hours under j\nhealth destroying conditions. The j\n-Healing system, with its irregular and\nexcessive hours, unhealthy workrooms\nand low rates of pay. has fastened it\nself on the crowded tenement districts\nof the larger cities. The twelve-hour\nworking day, notorious in the steel\nmills, prevails also in many other em\nployments. Thirty thousand wage\ni-a rners are killed hy industrial acci\ndents every year, nnd at least half a\nmillion seriously injured, a much heav\nier toll in human life than the indus\ntries of England and C-ermnny exact.\nI nder our employers' liability law, dis\n<aided by the rest of the civilized\n'ild. not more than one in eight of\nhe victims of industrial nccidents are\ninpensuted. Tn the last fifteen years\nr.OO workmen lost their lives in acci\ndents in coal mines of our state alone.\nIndustrial diseases, many of them\nrcvcntable, such as phosphorus nnd\nlead poisoning, to say nothing of tuber\ni iiplosis. continue to undermine the\nhealtfh, happiness and efficiency of un\ncounted thousands of workers. Unem\nployed, that most difficult problem, does\ni .t cease with return of prosperity, for\nmen and women nre hunting in vain for\nwork today. Here in the United States,\nthe land of opportunity, the weak nn.l\ndefenseless\u2014children, women, unskilled\nand unorganized men are the victims\nof a commercial nge of unregulated\ni iMpct it ion, and the whole community\nof which they arc a part suffers with\nthem.\nHence the organization of labor.\nUNIONS IN COPENHAGEN.\nSpeaking of the condition of union\ngrowth in Copenhagen, President Han\nsen in charge of the arrangements of\nihe international labor congress to be\nla id there Raid:\nThe lalair union movement is grow\ning incessantly. At the present time\nl lie projiortion of union workers is\n\u2022tionger here than in the entire world.\nI\u00bb ing flu per cent. Tn certain pursuits,\nas. for instance, the ty|Migraphers, there\nnot in Denmark a single worker that\ndoes not In-long to the union.\n\"At Copenhagen alone there are 100.\n--100 union members.\"\nSee the Union-made Men'i Suita at\nthe Boston Clothing Co.\nEIGHTH ANNIVERSARY NUMBER\nHence the effort of mankind who toil\nto gather together the oppressed of the\nshop, the factory tin- mill aud the mine\nin an effort to lighten the burdens. And\nthe burdens will be lightened, for the\nleavening power of education is com\ning to the aid of the workers, and they\nare learning that if they would be free\nof the ills that afflict them they must\nnave organization and education not\nonly themselves, but their children and\ntheir neighbors. And there is no time\nlike the present to do that, no time like\nLabor lhiy, no organization for that\npurpose like the labor union.\nWhile we have a degree of success in\nthe way of industrial organization, we\nare far from enjoying that degree of\npolitical power and unity which is most\nj desirable. We need to give greater time\n|aud closer thought to the close relation\nof politics to business; we need to in\nform ourselves more thoroughly regard\ning the possibilities of exercise of the\nfull power of citizenship; we need to\napply our leisure time less to pleasure\nthan to study the mental Improvement.\nBut these things will be done, nnd the\nfuture will hold in store for us greater\nprogress as workingmen and working\nwomen, greater enjoyment of the real\npowers and pleasures of life, for our\nwork is beuring fruit, and our people\narc Doming to the realization of what\nit means to be an American, an Ameri\ncan worker, an American citizen, a loyal\npatriot.\nThe principles for which the Ameri\ncan workingman has fought in his la\nbor union are spreading to all walks\nof life. The tyrant who oppressed the\nblack slave, the scoundrel who has ex\nploited the white workingman, the leech\nwho has fattened upon a cureless Amer\nlean public, are going down to dishonor\nand disgrace aud the future looks bright\nI for our organizations, for good govern\nment, for a higher American ideal than\nhas been cherished for half a century.\nCelebrate the day of Ijibor with joy.\nIt stands for the honor of humble men\n'and women who have made our country\none of the great nations of the world.\nAnd these men and women will, with\ntin- h'lp of the little red schoolhouse\nand its popular education, revolutionize\nthe tyranny of the few over the many.\nCelebrate with joy, for the outlook is\nglorious.\nHE DESERVES TO LOSE.\nNo man who is a candidate for the\nstnte legislature should hesitste to put\nhimself on record upon important ipies\ntions upon which he is asked to state\nhis position. The voters want to know\nV the name of the candidate, but\nhow he is going to vote if elected to\nrepresent them. This is but fair, and\nthe candidate who tries to get into\nthe legislature without, announcing the\nmain points in his platform and giving\nthe voters a chance to know where he\nstands is deserving of defeat.\nAnd the ambition of every lawyer is\nto become the aervant of a great rall\nroad, a trust or some other wealthy\ncorporation.\nTHE LABOR JOURNAL\nTHE OFFICIAL PAPER OF THE EVEKETT TRADES COUNCIL\nDevoted to the Interest\nLABOR DAY SHOULD PROVE\nWORTH OF ORGANIZATION\nThe following article from tlie Okla\nhoma Labor Unit hits the nail so\nsquarely on the head that we are forced\nIto reproduce it:\nKveryone who works for a living\nought to celebrate Labor Day. Every\nday ought to be a Labor Day insofar\nas bringing home the realization that\nthe workers who produce all that the\nworld consumes ought to receive all the\ngood things of this world; but when\nthere is but the day set apart by law\nas a holiday dedicated to the toilers\nof the land, then the toilers should\ngrasp this opportunity to celebrate.\nLabor Day brings us together. Craft\nj lines of deninrkation are wiped out, po\nlitica] differences are in the background,\nland even petty personal jealousies are\nforgotten. I-abor Day makes for agi\ntation, for federation, for education. It\nagitates the question of unionism in\nthe minds of non-unionists. It feder\nates, even though it may be for the day\nonly, the workers of different callings.\nIt is a golden opportunity for the edu\ncation of the workers in the true prin\nciples of unionism.\nHEREIN LIES THE VALUE OF UNIONISM\nLet him who questions tlie value of\nunionism pause to consider for a mo\nment just one thing that unionism has\naccomplished.\nIt is well known that fn the early\ndays of the present factory system the\nday's work extended usually to four\nteen or sixteen hours.\nThis long day existed for all workers,\nthe skilled and the unskilled, the chil\ndren as well as the men and women.\nThe workers had not yet learned to\norganize, and as individuals they were\nutterly helpless to effect a change in\nthe hours of their labor, or in the scale\nof their wages.\nThere were, of course, no laws to pro\ntest them, and so they lived entirely\nat the mercy of their employers.\nThe normal conditions that existed\nEVERETT. WASHINGTON. FRIDAY. SEPTEMBER 2. 1910\nSometimes we do not use the oppor\ntunity for education to the fullest ex\ntent. We are apt to make the day only\none of merry-making. The merry-mak\ning is well, too, for relaxation is good\nfor the mind and body. But we ought\nto be impressed with the lessons of the\nday, chief among them being the les\nson of the strength of solidarity. We\nought to realize that the marching col\numns are the greatest force in the com\nmunity. All the organizations of all\nthe oppressors and enemies of labor are\nchildishly weak in comparison with\norganized labor. On Labor Day we are\norganized. We can look at ourselves\nand see our strength, nnd we can see\nthat the strength is all in organization;\nnnd when we disintegrate we are weak\nagain.\nThe lesson we ought to learn is that\nwe will not disintegrate on the day\nafter Labor Day, but that we will stay\norganized. On every question that af\nfects us and our families we should get\ntogether and stay together. If some\nare too far advanced for the balance\nlittle more than half a lentury ago in\nKngland and elsewhere throughout the\nworld of the factory system are equall\ned today only in certain plague spots.\nWhen one reads the stories of the\nmisery and oppression, the long hours\nand low wages of those days, one won\nders how the workers managed to live\nat all.\nHow much the condition of the work\ner- generally has beecjJmproved it is\nby no means easy to*\u00ab\u00bb\u00bb!y. but we do\nknow that tlie condition of the workers\nhas vastly improved wherever they have\nlearned to value unity.\nIn those trades where the men have\nknown enough to fight for their rights\nand to stand together, there has arisen\nwhat some scoffers like to call an \"aris\ntocracy of labor.\"\nMILES POINDEXTER\nPeople i Candidate for United States Senate.\nof Organized Labor\nBy Robert Hunter\nthey ought to he willing lo wait a hit\nuntil the balance comes abreast, urg\ning, if they will, all the time. If some\nare lagging \"conservatives\" too far in\nthe. rear they ought to speed their foot\nsteps until they are abreast. United,\nthere is nothing that we cannot ob\ntain. Disunited, there is nothing we\ncan attain.\nSo let's begin by getting together\nDay. I>et every man who toils\nget in line for the big celebration. Let\nhim be present at roll call, bet there\nbe no vacant places. Let those who\nlabor but who do not belong to unions\n\u2014let them see the strength of unions:\nperhaps then they will realize that their\ninterests can best be served by mem\nbership in a labor organization. And\nlet our strength show those who oppress\nus. that we nre not so weak as they\nwould wish: perhaps then some of them\nwill realize that our organizations\ncould never have grown to such stand\nard without some good reason for ex\nistence.\nIt is up to YOU to celebrate Labor\nDay.\nAnd in certain trades there are in\ndeed aristocrats of labor, it is simply\nbecause they have had intelligence\nenough to fight together, to pay dues to\none organization, and to battle always\nwith unity and solidarity.\nAnd what they have done all other\nworkers can do.\nThe \"aristocrats\" hold no patent on\ntheir method of action, and by acting in\nthe same manner, all other toilers can\nwin all the \"aristocrats\" have won.\nNow it is difficult to ascertain just\nhow much union workers have benefited\nby higher wages.\nin that matter there is always tbe\nquestion as to the increased cost of\nliving which make difficult any com\nparison of wages here and abroad, or\n(Continued on Page Four.)\nFRANK MORRISON\nSecretary American Federation of Labor.\nSplendid Tribute to Poindexters Fearless\nRecord in Last Session of Congress\nBy Frank Morrison\nI am pleased to report that Mr.\nPoindexter has responded to our every\ncall, without evasion, without excuse\nand without hesitancy, and during the\nsession just closed, he voted for the fol\nlowing bills, which were passed and\nwhich are of interest to labor:\nRailroad Employers' Standardization\nof Equipment Bill (a safety appliance\nact i mi December 15, 1909.\nMine Workers' Bureau of Mines' Bill,\nJanuary 25, 1910.\nAmendment to the Employers' Lia\nbility Act, February 2:1. 1910.\n.Eight-hour Amendment to the Appro\npriatlon bill for the construction of bat\ntle ships, colliers and other vessels of\nthe navy, April 8. 1910.\nPostal Savings Bank bill, which\npassed the house June 2, 1910.\nBill grant ing second class mail rights\nfor trade union nnd frateinnl publica\ntions, which passed the house June 6,\nbut which failed to be reported out of\nthe senate committee during the last\nsession.\nMr. Poindexter introduced, at our re\nquest, the bill H. R. 19M6, in behalf\nof the civil rights of the civil service\nemployes of the United States govern\nment, nnd he did everything possible to i\nobtain a favorable report from the com\nmittee on civil service upon this bill.\nOn June 2. 1910. the house, while in\ncommittee on the whole, adopted the\nfollowing amendment, by Hughes, of!\nNew Jersey, in the section of the Sun 1\ndry Civil appropriation bill, making\nappropriation for the prosecution of\nviolation of the anti-trust law. This\nproviso was favored by labor.\n\"Provided further, that no part of\nthis money shall be spent in the prose\ncution of nny organization or individual\nfor entering into any combination or\nagreement having in view the increas\ning of wages, shortening of hours, or\nbettering the conditions of labor, or for\nany act done in furthering thereof not\nin itself unlawful.\"\nOn June 9. this proviso was stricken\nfrom the hill when it was reported to\nthe senate by the appropriation com\ninittee. On a record vote of 34 yoa\u00ab\n16 nays and 42 not voting, the senate\nsustained the action of the nppropria\ntion committee.\nOn June 21. a motion was made in\nthe house to instruct the conferees to\ninsist upon disagreeing with the senate.\nThe motion carried by a vote of 151\nyeas to 105 nays, 12 answering prcs\nent and 119 not voting. This record\nvote in the house was an endorsement\nof its former action in favor of the\nHughes amendment when it was added\nWe are ruled in this country by law\nyers, upper class lawyers.\nThey dominate our legislatures, our\ncongress and our courts.\nOne of the most distinguished repre\nsentatives of that profession nits today\nin the presidential chair at Washing\nton.\nIn the present United States senate\nthere are fifty lawyers, three farmers,\ntwo manufacturers, five bankers, five\npublic officisls, one stock raiser, etc.\nHAVE YOU\nREGISTERED\n110 the hill while the house was in com\nmit lee of the whole.\nMr, Poindexter ii recorded as voting\naye on that date, or in favor of the\nproviso.\nOn June 23, the conferees reported\nto the house a disagreement on this pro\nvise ami recommended \"that the house\nrecede and concur.\" which meant that\ntin 1 house agree with the senate and\neliminate th,' Hughes proviso from the\nbill. The net ion c arried by a vote of\nLIS yeas to 130 nays. 16 answering\npresent and 108 not voting. By this\nvote the house of representatives re\npuliatad its former actions taken on\nJune 2 and Line 21. when it adopted\nthe Hughes amendment and instructed\nits conferees to retain it in the hill.\nThis last vote was the determining fac\ntor in which the house of representa\ntives placed itself on record as being\nopposed to any organization or Individ\nilia mil.ing an organized effort to in\ncrease wages, to reduce hours, or to\nbetter the condition of labor\u2014organized\nor unorganised \u2014without running the\nrisk of criminal prosecution under the\nprovisions of the anti-Trust Law.\nOn mis final and most important\nvote. Mr. Poindexter is recorded as vot\ning nay. or in favor of retaining the\nproviso, and while the discussion was on\nin the house, Mr. Poindexter was ac\ntively endeavoring to s-<juro support\nfor this very essential amendment to\nthe Sundry Civil Appropriation bill.\nDuring the session of congress just\nclosed. Mr. Poindexter took a very ac\ntive part in the house \"in favor of re\nstoring genuine representative govern\nment.\" He vigorously opposed the arbi\ntrary house rules and the more nrbi\ntrary interpretation of them by Speaker\nCannon. Kvery credit should lie given\nto Mr. Poindexter for his indefatigable\nand successful work in this direction.\nMr. Poindexter has declared himself in\nfavor of the Wilson hill, H. R. 25288,\ngrunting relief from injunction abuse\naud including an amendment to the\nSherman anti-trust act.\nHe has declared himself in favor of.\nand he worked faithfully and vigorously\nto secure the enactment of the eight\nhour bill. H. R. 15441. He has given\ni very evidence of being faithful to his\ngreat trust and has never hesitated to\nserve the cause of labor and the best\ninterests of all the people, whenever\nthe opportunity has lieen affordeo him.\nIn short. Representative Poindexter is\none of the men that we relied n|>on to\nadvance nnd promote legislation of the\nhighest value. He did all that one man\ncould lie expected to do, especially dur\ning his first term in congress.\nOUR HIGHER RULERS\nIn the house of representatives there\nare two hundred and twelve lawyers,\nsixty four public officials, sixteen far\nmors, nineteen bankers, etc.\nIn both houses the large majority is\nmade up of lawyers.\nNow lawyers are a peculiar breed of\nthe serving class.\nThey may begin by handling the\ncases of the poor, but if they are bright\naud able they end by handling the cases\nof the rich.\nNo. 33.","height":"29132","width":"21360"}}
